            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Purchasing/RFQs — Advanced Reference\n\nThis is reference material for power users and admins. It covers the edge-case mechanics behind the RFQ feature that the core Overview, Walkthrough, Field Reference, and Quiz modules intentionally skip. For the everyday flow (create an RFQ, send to vendors, record responses, award), use those core modules instead.\n\n## Capability Gating (CAP-P2P-RFQ)\n\nThe entire Purchasing feature is gated behind the capability **CAP-P2P-RFQ** (\"Request for quote (multi-vendor sourcing)\"). Key facts:\n\n- **Off by default.** CAP-P2P-RFQ ships with `IsDefaultOn: false`, so on a fresh install Purchasing is hidden until an admin enables it at `/admin/capabilities`. Shops that buy from a fixed vendor (no competitive sourcing) typically leave it off.\n- **Enforced at the controller.** `PurchasingController` carries `[RequiresCapability(\"CAP-P2P-RFQ\")]`, so every RFQ endpoint (list, create, detail, update, send, record-response, compare, award) short-circuits with a 403 capability envelope when the capability is disabled — not just the menu item.\n- **Area:** P2P (Procure-to-Pay). Enabling it is what makes the RFQ the front end of the PO flow; with it off, you create Purchase Orders directly against a vendor instead.\n\n## Role Gating (Admin / Manager / OfficeManager)\n\n`PurchasingController` is decorated with `[Authorize(Roles = \"Admin,Manager,OfficeManager\")]`. Consequences:\n\n- Only **Admin**, **Manager**, and **OfficeManager** can use any RFQ endpoint — list, create, send, record responses, compare, or award. There is no separate read-only role; if you can see RFQs, you can act on them.\n- Roles such as Engineer, Worker, or Sales have no access to Purchasing/RFQs, even though Engineer can touch vendor catalog data elsewhere (CAP-MD-VENDORS).\n- Both gates apply together: a user needs one of the three roles **and** the install must have CAP-P2P-RFQ enabled.\n\n## How RFQs Reach Cancelled / Expired\n\nThe RFQ status enum has seven values — Draft, Sent, Receiving, Evaluating, Awarded, Cancelled, Expired — and the list page lets you filter by all of them. But the live status transitions the code actually performs are only:\n\n- **Draft → Sent** — on the Send to Vendors action (`SendToVendorsAsync`).\n- **Sent → Receiving** — automatically when the first vendor response is recorded (`RecordVendorResponse`, only if the RFQ is still Sent).\n- **(any non-terminal) → Awarded** — on Award (`AwardAndCreatePoAsync`).\n\nThere is **no endpoint, handler, service method, or background job that sets an RFQ to Cancelled, Expired, or Evaluating.** Those three statuses exist in the enum and in the filter/chip vocabulary but are not reachable through any current UI action — no Cancel button, no auto-expire job watching the Response Deadline. Treat Cancelled and Expired as forward-looking/placeholder states: a filter on them returns nothing on a normal install. The Evaluating status is likewise defined but never auto-set; comparison happens while the RFQ is in Receiving.\n\n## Edit Reachability (Draft-Only, Not Surfaced)\n\nA PUT `rfqs/{id}` endpoint and `UpdateRfqHandler` exist, but edit is tightly constrained:\n\n- **Draft-only on the server.** `UpdateRfqHandler` throws `InvalidOperationException(\"Can only edit RFQs in Draft status\")` whenever the RFQ status is anything other than Draft. Once an RFQ is Sent, its part/quantity/dates are frozen — you cannot rewrite a request vendors are already quoting.\n- **Not surfaced in the UI today.** The Angular `PurchasingService` has an `updateRfq()` method, but no component invokes it — there is no Edit button on the list or the detail dialog. In practice, an RFQ's fields are effectively set at creation; to change a still-Draft RFQ you would call the endpoint directly. (The same `CreateRfqRequestModel` shape is reused for both create and update.)\n- **Net effect:** the create dialog is the only authored field-entry surface. If a Draft RFQ is wrong, the practical path is to recreate it.\n\n## Status-Transition Summary\n\n| Action | API | Status effect |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Create RFQ | POST rfqs | new RFQ in Draft |\n| Send to Vendors | POST rfqs/{id}/send | Draft → Sent; one Pending response per invited vendor |\n| Record Response | POST rfqs/{id}/responses | Sent → Receiving (first response only); that response → Received |\n| Award | POST rfqs/{id}/award/{responseId} | → Awarded; winner Awarded, others Not Awarded; PO generated |\n| Edit | PUT rfqs/{id} | fields updated; rejected unless status is Draft |\n| Cancel / Expire | (none) | no code path sets Cancelled or Expired |","sections":[]}"""
        });

